snippet.textDisplay:
One huge benefit of taxpayer-funded "free" public transport is that we waste no money on ticket machines, ticket-controllers, software and information distribution. A person who drives for work every day has no barrier to taking the train on the weekend, and for the days they do drive there's less traffic, less congestion and therefore less cost in gas and emissions.


"Free" public transport is just an all-round win that would help the EU get a hell of a lot closer to its climate goals if all its members did it.

Offering a Free & improved public transit system makes a lot of sense, when you compare it with the present system. Here is some of the time & money that they can save by using public transportation.
1) Less funds needed for new roads & highways to accommodate more cars.
2) Savings from loss of productivity for all the people who are stuck in traffic.
3) Less Heath-care costs due to contamination.
4) Less risk of losing life & property as compared to using automobiles.
5) Savings in car ownership, fuel & maintenance.

snippet.textDisplay:
€4 per day on minimum wage definitely does have a significant impact.
Compare to the racket in the UK.
I live in Glasgow where an all day bus ticket is £4.70 / €5.64 - that's bus only - not train, not Underground.
A return ticket on the Underground is £3.30 / €3.96 irrespective of length of journey, and Glasgow's subway system is absolutely tiny, only serving a fraction of the city.
A return ticket on the railway from the suburbs will cost in the region of £4 - 5 / €4.80 - €6.
Unlike many other cities across Europe, it's impossible to buy an all day ticket for all modes of public transport.
The public transport infrastructure, (aside from the subway) is actually reasonably good, but it is incredibly expensive, yet there doesn't appear to be anyone willing to address the situation.
I'd be absolutely overjoyed at the thought of spending €4 / approximately £3.30 on an all day ticket useable on multiple modes of transport.

snippet.textDisplay:
There is one point to be said in favor of free transit though, convenience.
It not much, but having to pay is a bit of hassle. When I travel short distances in my town, I sometimes find myself choosing to walk instead, because although the cost might be small, it's a bit of hassle adding to the waiting for a train, etc etc. It's just easier to walk if it's a short distance. Unless I have a 30day pass, in which case it's just a matter of walking down and wait for a train.
I think the importance of not having to pay is a bit underrated in this video. But then again, I am not familiar with Luxemburg's transit system, maybe it's really bad? I know that for people who are used to traveling by car, it is!

snippet.textDisplay:
No train for 90 minutes?

Meanwhile I was on an international service from Germany to the Netherlands, which was certainly nowhere near being free, that was delayed around the border for 4 hours.
4!

I've been waiting for trains in England at times that are 6 hours late (though that was a long time ago)
But trains being 30-40 minutes late happens fairly regularly, and England has some of the most expensive fares on the planet.

And buses... Ooh boy. Buses that are an hour late, crowded, expensive...

Paying doesn't guarantee good service.
Even where tickets are extremely expensive, that STILL doesn't guarantee good service.

Because unfortunately the amount paid for the service by the end user frequently has little to do with the quality of the service unless there is a LOT of direct competition.

And in public transport? There is hardly EVER direct competition.

Do you know what rail privatisation did to the UK?
It created a bunch of regional monopolies is what.

Seriously, try and get to your destination in the UK and see how many of the routes are served by more than one company...
It's basically none bar the most busy routes in existence.

Even where two companies operate from the same station, frequently they go to completely different destinations, rendering any idea of 'competition' moot.

Cost to the end user does not correlate to service quality, unfortunately.

snippet.textDisplay: Great, in my country (The Netherlands) prices of public transport rise every year, some years with as much as 8%. It's even worse than that. I have to take a bus to work that, besides the standard fee, charges €2 extra for every time I take it. It's forcing people into cars.. The Netherlands is going the wrong way. I think they might be doing this so that in the future they can say: 'Free transport? But the government budget only supports public transport by 25% so that would mean to big an increase!' And over here sometimes I have to wait for an hour for a bus that usually comes every ten minutes. In a non-crowded residential area with good connections fo the city center as well as the highways. It's crazy to hear some people complain about a train being 1,5 hours late and it being an extremely rare case.
